Meet my friend Zoi, who I've had the pleasure of knowing for 3 years. Zoi and I were on the opening team of @nordstromnyc. Zoi speaks multiple languages and is a lifelong learner; always eager to better herself. Zoi consistently turns up for her friends—now it's time to support her in return.

Zoi moved to America from Greece 3.5 years ago and purchased a home in 3 years - persevering through the pandemic and budgeting wisely.

Two months after purchasing her home, Zoi was diagnosed with an aggressive and invasive form of breast cancer. Zoi continues to work full-time during her chemo treatments and is the sole earner for her medical bills. Next month, Zoi will go through surgery and will be unable to work. She will face a significant loss of wages - with mounting medical bills and mortgage payments still due.

I've created this fundraiser for Zoi because no one enduring cancer should worry about bills or financial collapse. At this time, Zoi needs to focus on healing - and with your love and support, we can turn up for her.

Link in my profile.

In March of 2011 I purchased a brand new @schwinnbikes Cruiser from Target. I named it “Strawberry” because my car, a blue Volkswagen Beetle, was named “Blüeberry.” The bike cost $112.00 and I had to borrow $10 from my roommate because my debit card declined (E-PASS automatically charged me - FL toll system. I promise I paid her back!) We put that bicycle in the backseat of my beetle and I’d call that bicycle mine for the next 12 years. 🚲❤️

The purchase seems so minimal now, but I saved for that bicycle week after week and it brought me so much joy throughout the years. When I purchased my Fiat in 2014, I remember feeling so proud that I was able to purchase a car like that with my art degrees; that I was making a living doing what I love. I sold that Fiat 9 months later and moved to NYC. 🚗

but Strawberry, the bicycle, came with me. 

Strawberry was harder to get rid of than most things I own. I’m not a materialistic person but it was a symbol of my hard work. I rode that bike through Atlanta, to work at SCAD, to modeling gigs, throughout COVID. I rode that bicycle to school the day of my MFA thesis defense. I rode that bike through snowstorms, beaches, hard times and great times. I’ll miss that bike, but it was time to move on, and today I took Strawberry on it’s last ride. 

Yesterday I walked past @togabikes and the staff was so friendly and helpful. I finally decided it was time to get a new bike, something I could ride easier around the city with Andrew… so… welcome my new @cannondaleroad bicycle: “Limewire!” 

If you’re still reading, here’s an Easter egg: I downloaded limewire pro with limewire when I was in middle school because I am an advanced thinker 💪🏽

On this International Women’s Day, I want to recognize @ebradyrobinson. 📸

Brady was a professor of mine in graduate school. She made sure we had a thorough understanding of professional practices; how to write about our art, ourselves and how to get into (and produce) exhibitions. 

I’ve leaned on Brady, who has always been a call away, in every job switch I’ve made - and she’s always given me great advice and support. 

Brady is hilarious, incredibly smart and cares deeply about her students and photo industry. I‘ve been out of college for a decade and she continues to inspire and motivate me regularly. I’m sure I’m not the only one. 

Thank you Brady, for sharing so much of yourself and your knowledge with us, especially in this industry filled with gatekeeping and glass ceilings. I owe so much to you and am forever grateful.

#internationalwomensday #ebradyrobinson #ebradyrobinsonstudio #womenhelpingwomen

Join @ashoksinhaphoto and @nienass at @foleygallery / @launchphotobooks on Wednesday, March 29th at 7pm for an evening of conversation and American nostalgia as they discuss his series “Gas and Glamour.” 

For more information or to acquire work, send us a DM or email us at info@treatgallery.org. 

Ashok Sinha is an architectural and fine art photographer whose large-scale photographs capture a sense of place tied to both natural landscapes and built environments. He fell in love with architecture while photographing Brazilian architect Oscar Niemeyer's masterpiece Niteroi Contemporary Art Museum in Rio de Janeiro on a travel assignment. His photographs have been published by editorial outlets such as The New York Times, Architectural Digest, Interior Design, and exhibited at The Museum of the City of New York, the International Center of Photography, and The Royal Photographic Society.
Ashok drove 2,500 miles shooting Gas and Glamour, an art book of Los Angeles roadside buildings from the golden age of car culture. It was chosen by both The Wall Street Journal and Los Angeles Magazine as a top photo book in 2020, and The Guardian review called it “easy to get lost in nostalgia, and even escapism, looking at Sinha’s photographs.”

In 2020, I was a juror for @photolucida’s #criticalmass. During my jurying, I was introduced to the incredible work of @galinakurlat. Galina’s art absolutely blew me away and I knew I had to work with her someday! After a couple small shows and fairs, I’m thrilled for Galina’s solo booth to premiere at @voltaartfairs tomorrow with @treatgallery. 15% of sales will be donated to @lehelps. 

Galina examines the connection between subject and medium, by embracing the imperfections and possibilities of process-based photography. Using traditional darkroom techniques, including wet collodion, expired Polaroid film, and lumen prints, she addresses identity, intimacy, and uncertainty. There is a latent spark in analog photographic processes which inspires her practice; experimentation is as essential as the outcome.

Kurlat’s work is an ongoing investigation into the body as vulnerable and ever-changing. The subjects range from figurative portraiture to abstractions made with saliva, blood, hair, bathwater, and breastmilk. In every iteration, there is a consistent connection to the corporeal. Like flesh, these images change with time, recognizable features fade, and gestures disappear, obscuring identity. Between beauty and decay a truth is revealed ––an ambiguous truth that asks more questions than it answers.

In 2022, Galina was the recipient of the prestigious @hopperprize. 

treat gallery is a philanthropic project by Sherri Nienass Littlefield.

Little Essentials offers at-risk families living in poverty urgently needed children’s supplies and parenting education to promote the health, well-being, and safety of their children under five years of age. In partnership with Tribeca Pediatrics and other organizations, Little Essentials offers free educational workshops for all NYC residents living in poverty, from maternal health and infant care to GED preparation, housing rights, and advocacy, financial literacy, support for parents of students with disabilities, early reader literacy and more.

Very excited to have this image currently up at @nordstromnyc! Kris Graves is incredible and I’ve been trying to get his work featured for a few years now. This stunning image is from his iconic “Testament” project. 

“The Testament Project is an exploration and re-conception of the contemporary black experience in America. More often than not, black people are portrayed in the extreme - either as very rich or very poor, they are demonized, infantilized, ridiculed, idolized or hyper-sexualized; and within the art canon there is a noticeable scarcity of black representation. In the glowing portraits, I give control of the colored lighting to my subjects, in order to create a space that is participatory and empowered. By including my subjects in the creation of the scene and the altering of color, I seek to create photographs that portray individuality in addition to their blackness.”

I especially love this adorable piece from one of my favorite artists (painting one of my favorite subjects!) @jjgallowaystudios.

The title, Curious Spontaneity lends itself to one of Nordstrom’s core values; Curious and Ever Changing. Invited artists were challenged to create work capturing emotions associated with yellow: Joy, Happiness, Optimism, Playfulness, Confidence and Curiosity.

Exhibitors include Brian Bills, Kris Graves, JJ Galloway, Amie Hollmann, Matt LaBoone, Matt Mele, Mark Liam Smith, E. Brady Robinson, Emily Cate Sabree, Alison Jones, Leza Lin, Lay-Ing Oji, Gail Postal, Susan Rosenfeld and Jonathan Taub.

This feature is in partnership with the Art Students League of New York, an iconic institution run by artists for artists. ASL provides students opportunities to receive hands-on studio education taught by leading fine artists.

We’ll be exhibiting new pieces from @vacancyphoto, @you_hadid_me_at_hello, @kikiaranita, @galinakurlat, @markliamsmith & @parsleyoooo. 15% of sales will be donated directly to the Sylvia Rivera Law Project, -and- $100 from each “Love is Love” print form Mark Liam Smith will be donated to the SRLP.

A New Year’s resolution of mine is to take more photos. I love dealing photography but as I grow in that field, my own practice has decreased over the years. Someone recently asked what some of my favorite photos are. In no particular order, and for various reason, here are some of my favorites. 📸

1. Henri Cartier-Bresson - “Romania,” 1975

2. Ormond Gigli - “Girls in the Windows,” 1960

3. Guy Bourdin - (Charles Jourdan Advertisement,) 1975

4. Daniel Handal - “Yellow Factor American Singer,” 2016

5. Jason DeMarte - “Blue Mourning,” 2016

6. Lauren Greenfield - “High School Seniors,” 2011

7. Terry Richardson - “Marilyn Manson’s Dad,” (Paper Magazine,” 2015

8. Brian Ulrich - “Randall Park Mall,” 2008

9. LaToya Ruby Frazier - (From “The Notion of Family,”) 2014
